"""
MKT Christ — Luke 4–5
Output: data/commentary/mkt-christ/luke.json

Ch4: Temptation as second-Adam / new-Israel recapitulation; Nazareth Isa 61
  proclamation as direct fulfillment claim; exorcisms as invasion of Satan's
  domain; healing as Isa 53:4 fulfillment.
Ch5: Miraculous catch anticipating Ezek 47 and fishers-of-men mission;
  leper-cleansing as touching the untouchable; Son of Man's authority to forgive
  sins (paralytic); Levi's call forming the new community; bridegroom saying
  and new wine/wineskins as covenant-fulfillment and covenant-newness.

Christ-level classifications used throughout:
  direct   = NT explicitly cites this verse as fulfilled in Christ
  type     = OT person/institution/event structurally anticipates Christ
  shadow   = broader pattern pointing forward
  theme    = shared theological theme OT-NT
  revelation of God = reveals God's character expressed fully in Christ
"""
import json, pathlib
ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists(): return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    # INTENT: merge new_data into existing without overwriting any present entry
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing: existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]: existing[ch][v] = html

NEW = {
'4': {
'1': '<p>The Spirit who descended on Jesus at his baptism (3:22) now leads him into the wilderness. This is not accidental geography: the wilderness is where Israel was tested for forty years (Deut 8:2-5) and where Adam\'s descendants have always proved faithless. Jesus enters as the representative human, "full of the Holy Spirit" (pl&#275;r&#275;s pneumatos hagiou) -- the Spirit who was promised to the Servant (Isa 42:1: "I will put my Spirit on him") and who marks the one anointed to inaugurate the new covenant. The theme: the Spirit-anointed Son now undergoes the definitive test that Israel failed.</p>',
'2': '<p>Forty days of testing echoes Israel\'s forty years of wilderness testing (Deut 8:2) and Moses\'s forty days on Sinai (Exod 34:28). The number is typological: forty = a complete period of testing and proving. Where Israel repeatedly failed in the wilderness (Ex 16: bread; Ex 17: water; Num 11: desire for Egypt), Jesus succeeds. The devil\'s testing targets the same vulnerabilities Israel exhibited: bread (provision), power (lordship), and divine protection (presumption). Jesus is the new Israel, recapitulating Israel\'s history from the inside and succeeding where they failed.</p>',
'3': '<p>The first temptation targets identity and provision: "If you are the Son of God, tell this stone to become bread." The "if" (ei + indicative = since you are, not doubting it) is a conditional that assumes the fact: the devil is probing whether Jesus will use divine sonship for self-provision. The hunger is real (v.2: he ate nothing for forty days). But Jesus refuses to leverage divine identity for personal comfort. The temptation recapitulates Israel craving bread in the wilderness (Exod 16; Num 11) -- and anticipates the loaves miracle (9:13-17) where Jesus feeds others by the same power he refuses to use for himself.</p>',
'4': '<p>"Man shall not live on bread alone" is a direct citation of Deut 8:3 (LXX), where Moses explains the manna: God let Israel hunger "to teach you that man does not live on bread alone but on every word that comes from the mouth of God." Jesus\'s citation is not an abstract theological point but the announcement of his own principle: the word of God -- not miraculous provision -- is the bread of his life. This establishes the Christological pattern: Jesus subordinates everything, including physical need, to the Father\'s word. Theologically, it frames the incarnation: the Son became truly hungry and truly dependent on the Father\'s word.</p>',
'5': '<p>The second temptation\'s panorama of "all the kingdoms of the world in an instant" (en stigm&#275; chronou = in a moment of time) is a vision of what Jesus came to receive by a different path: Ps 2:8 promises the Son "the nations as your inheritance, and the ends of the earth as your possession." The devil offers what is genuinely the Son\'s inheritance -- but by a shortcut that bypasses the cross. The temptation is not to receive something that doesn\'t belong to Jesus but to receive what does belong to him on the devil\'s terms rather than the Father\'s. This is the eschatological temptation of all Christology: the kingdom without the cross.</p>',
'6': '<p>"It has been given to me, and I can give it to anyone I want to" -- the devil\'s claim is partially true: he is "the ruler of this world" (John 12:31; 14:30; 16:11; 2 Cor 4:4: "the god of this age"). The "kingdoms of the world" do operate under demonic influence, which is why John writes "the whole world is under the control of the evil one" (1 John 5:19). The temptation exploits a real theological fact. The devil\'s offer is genuine but the terms are corrupt: receiving the kingdoms from the devil means acknowledging his authority, which would undo the entire mission of rescuing humanity from that very authority (Col 2:15; Heb 2:14).</p>',
'7': '<p>"If you worship me, it will all be yours" -- the demand for worship (proskyneseis moi = you shall bow down to me) is the nakedly idolatrous core of the offer. The command is the same word used in Ps 97:7 (LXX) where all gods (idols) are commanded to bow to the LORD. To bow to the devil would be to invert the cosmic order -- the Son of God acknowledging the usurper\'s claim to universal sovereignty. This is the temptation toward which all idolatry tends: preferring an immediate, visible, this-worldly good over the invisible, costly, covenanted good of the Father\'s will. Jesus refuses because he knows what true worship means: it is owed only to the Father.</p>',
'8': '<p>"Worship the Lord your God and serve him only" -- Deut 6:13 (LXX) is the second Deuteronomy citation, from the section immediately following the Shema (Deut 6:4: "Hear O Israel, the LORD our God, the LORD is one"). The exclusive worship of YHWH is the covenantal foundation of Israel\'s identity -- the first commandment applied. Jesus\'s citation is his refusal to be the kind of messiah who achieves dominion through any means other than the Father\'s appointed path. This establishes the entire logic of the passion: the cross is not a defeat but the Father\'s appointed means of the Son\'s ultimate glorification (Phil 2:9-11).</p>',
'9': '<p>The third temptation moves to the Jerusalem temple -- the dwelling place of God, the center of Israel\'s worship, the place Jesus has just declared as the Father\'s house (2:49). The pinnacle of the temple (to pterygion tou hierou = the wing/pinnacle of the temple -- probably the royal portico overlooking the Kidron Valley) is the place where God\'s presence is most concentrated. The devil now uses Scripture (Ps 91:11-12: "he will command his angels to guard you") to tempt Jesus to leverage divine protection for spectacular self-validation. The temptation is to force a sign that will compel belief -- to shortcut the slow path of patient proclamation.</p>',
'10': '<p>Psalm 91:11-12 is cited by the devil as warrant for the leap: "He will command his angels concerning you to guard you carefully." The psalm is a promise of divine protection for the one who trusts in God (Ps 91:1-2: "Whoever dwells in the shelter of the Most High will rest in the shadow of the Almighty"). The devil weaponizes a genuine promise of protection by stripping it from its context of humble trust. This is the exegetical temptation: using true Scripture to support a false conclusion. The NT\'s use of Ps 91 is always in the register of trust (never presumption) -- here the contrast between trust and presumption is the theological point.</p>',
'11': '<p>"They will lift you up in their hands" -- the angelic protection promised in Ps 91 is real (cf. v.43: an angel strengthens Jesus in Gethsemane). But the fulfillment of the promise comes through suffering faithfully borne, not by demanding that God demonstrate his protection on demand. The angels who will serve Jesus come at the Father\'s timing, not at a spectacular self-chosen moment. This verse anticipates the cross: Jesus will hang on a cross without angels preventing his death, because Ps 91\'s protection is not a guarantee against death but the assurance of ultimate vindication -- the resurrection being the definitive "lifting up."</p>',
'12': '<p>"Do not put the Lord your God to the test" -- Deut 6:16 (LXX), citing Israel\'s test of God at Massah (Exod 17:7): "Is the LORD among us or not?" Israel\'s demand for water was fundamentally a demand for God to prove himself. Jesus refuses to demand that the Father prove his faithfulness by a spectacular intervention. This third citation completes the pattern: all three temptations are met with the covenant principles of Deut 6-8 -- the sections of Deuteronomy where Moses explains the meaning of the wilderness testing. Jesus knows the Torah at depth, not merely as proof-texts: he inhabits the covenant framework that Israel was supposed to embody.</p>',
'13': '<p>"When the devil had finished all this tempting, he left him until an opportune time" (achri kairou = until an appropriate/opportune season) -- Luke alone notes that the temptation is suspended, not ended. The "opportune time" returns in the passion: 22:3 ("Satan entered Judas") and 22:53 ("this is your hour -- when darkness reigns"). The temptation narrative is not merely the story of Jesus\'s moral victory at the beginning of his ministry but the opening scene of a cosmic conflict that will reach its climax at the cross. The devil departs to return when the moment is more strategically favorable -- and the cross will be that moment of darkness\'s maximum effort.</p>',
'14': '<p>"Jesus returned to Galilee in the power of the Spirit" -- the return from the wilderness mirrors Israel\'s return from Sinai (Exod 19-40) and anticipates the Spirit-empowered mission of Acts 1:8. The "power of the Spirit" (en t&#275; dynamei tou pneumatos) is the Spirit promised by Isaiah (Isa 61:1: "The Spirit of the Lord is on me") and by John (3:16: "one more powerful than I"). Jesus\'s Galilean ministry is not the work of a merely human teacher but the Spirit-empowered fulfillment of prophetic expectation. Every healing, teaching, and exorcism that follows is an act of the anointed Servant operating under divine commission.</p>',
'15': '<p>Jesus teaching in the synagogues and being praised by everyone stands in contrast to the rejection at Nazareth (v.28-30) and foreshadows the pattern of the entire Gospel and Acts: initial positive response, then intensifying opposition, then the decisive rejection. The synagogue as venue is significant: Jesus does not establish a new institution but operates within Israel\'s existing structure. He comes as the fulfillment of what the synagogue assembled to hear (Torah and Prophets) -- not as its abolisher but its culmination (Matt 5:17: "I have not come to abolish them but to fulfill them").</p>',
'16': '<p>Jesus "went to Nazareth, where he had been brought up, and on the Sabbath day he went into the synagogue as was his custom." The custom of Sabbath synagogue attendance is assumed; Jesus is a practicing Jew. The Nazareth synagogue scene is programmatic in Luke: Luke places it first as the keynote of the entire ministry, whereas Mark (6:1-6) places it later. The Isaiah scroll is handed to him -- a direct, providential fulfillment. The detail that Jesus "stood up to read" (anesté anagn&#333;nai) follows the synagogue practice: one sat to teach, stood to read Scripture. The posture marks the formal reading of the Torah/Prophets portion.</p>',
'17': '<p>The scroll of Isaiah is "handed to him" (epedothē = was given to him, divine passive). Finding the specific passage of Isa 61:1-2 (whether Jesus searched for it or it was the appointed reading for that Sabbath is debated) is presented as a purposeful act. Isaiah\'s scroll was the prophetic book of comfort, anticipating the Servant\'s mission. The specific passage Jesus reads is the Servant\'s self-description as the anointed herald of Jubilee. The scene presents Jesus as the reader who is also the subject of what he reads -- the one who finds himself described in the scroll he is opening.</p>',
'18': '<p>Isaiah 61:1-2a is a direct Christological text cited here as direct fulfillment: "The Spirit of the Lord is on me, because he has anointed me (kechriston me = has anointed me -- the root of christos) to proclaim good news to the poor." The fourfold mission (good news to poor, release to captives, recovery of sight to blind, freedom for oppressed) maps directly onto Jesus\'s subsequent ministry in Luke-Acts. "He has sent me to proclaim release to the captives" (aphesin aichmalotois = release/forgiveness to captives) uses the same word (aphesis) as "forgiveness of sins" -- the vocabulary of both physical liberation and spiritual forgiveness deliberately overlap.</p>',
'19': '<p>"To proclaim the year of the Lord\'s favor" (eniauton kyriou dekton = the acceptable/favorable year of the Lord) is the Jubilee year of Lev 25: every fifty years all debts were cancelled, all land returned to original owners, all Hebrew slaves freed. Jesus stops before reading Isa 61:2b ("the day of vengeance of our God") -- the truncation is deliberate. The first coming announces the year of favor; the second coming will bring the day of vengeance. The Jubilee is the direct OT background: Jesus is the one who enacts the ultimate Jubilee -- the release from debt, bondage, and the effects of the Fall -- in his death and resurrection.</p>',
'20': '<p>"Then he rolled up the scroll, gave it back to the attendant and sat down" -- the scroll is returned; Jesus sits (the teaching posture). "The eyes of everyone in the synagogue were fastened on him" (ēsan atenizontes = were intently fixed on him -- the same word as Pentecost and Stephen\'s vision in Acts). The intense gaze of the congregation is the moment of anticipation before the proclamation of v.21. Every element of the scene -- the scroll, the sitting, the watching eyes -- contributes to the expectation of a decisive word. The silence and attention signal that something extraordinary is about to be said.</p>',
'21': '<p>"Today this scripture is fulfilled in your hearing" -- the single sentence that interprets everything: Jesus is the direct fulfillment of Isa 61:1-2. "Today" (s&#275;meron = today) is Luke\'s eschatological marker throughout the Gospel (2:11: "today a Savior has been born"; 4:21; 19:9: "Today salvation has come to this house"; 23:43: "Today you will be with me in paradise"). The "today" of fulfillment is the "today" of salvation: Jesus\'s presence makes the prophetic promise current and actual. This is not a prediction but a declaration: the anointed Servant is here, and the Jubilee has begun. This verse is the explicit announcement of what the entire Gospel narrative enacts.</p>',
'22': '<p>The initial positive response ("All spoke well of him and were amazed at the gracious words that came from his lips") gives way to the suspicious question: "Isn\'t this Joseph\'s son?" The acknowledgment of Jesus as a local boy creates a stumbling block. The people want to relate to Jesus as a familiar person -- a neighbor from a known family -- rather than as the fulfillment of Isaiah\'s prophecy. This anticipates the Christological paradox: the Word made flesh (John 1:14) is always scandalously particular. The Son of God is also Joseph\'s son; the divine Servant is also the Nazareth carpenter\'s son.</p>',
'23': '<p>"Physician, heal yourself" -- the proverb inverted: Jesus is the Physician who heals others but not himself, because his own suffering is the means of others\' healing (Isa 53:4-5: "he took up our pain and bore our suffering... by his wounds we are healed"). The demand "do here in your hometown what we have heard you did in Capernaum" is the demand for the Messiah to prove himself to those with the most natural claim on him. The rejection of the hometown prophet anticipates the passion: Jerusalem will make the same demand at the cross (23:35: "save yourself if you are God\'s Messiah, the Chosen One").</p>',
'24': '<p>"No prophet is accepted in his home town" -- the pattern of rejected prophets runs through OT history: Elijah (1 Kgs 19:10), Elisha (2 Kgs 2:23-24), Jeremiah (Jer 11:21; 12:6), and others. Jesus identifies himself in this prophetic succession. Stephen\'s speech (Acts 7:51-52) will apply the same pattern to the entire history of Israel\'s rejection of God\'s messengers: "Was there ever a prophet your ancestors did not persecute?" Jesus\'s rejection at Nazareth is not an isolated incident but the first instance of the defining pattern of his ministry: the one sent is rejected by those to whom he was sent.</p>',
'25': '<p>The Elijah example: Elijah was sent to a Gentile widow in Zarephath (Sidon) during a three-and-a-half-year famine (1 Kgs 17:1, 8-16). The "three and a half years" echoes Dan 12:7 (the period of tribulation) and will reappear in Rev 11:3 as the period of the two witnesses\' ministry. Elijah\'s ministry in Sidon -- outside Israel, to a non-Israelite -- demonstrates that Israel\'s prophets were not proprietary assets of the nation. The Gentile widow received the miracle that Israel\'s widows did not. The Christological resonance: Jesus\'s mission will extend beyond Israel (Acts 13:46; 28:28) because Israel repeatedly rejects the one sent to them.</p>',
'26': '<p>"Elijah was not sent to any of them, but to a widow in Zarephath in the region of Sidon" -- Zarephath (modern Sarafand, Lebanon) was in Phoenicia, the territory of Baal-worship (1 Kgs 16:31: Jezebel was from Sidon). The widow who received Elijah was a Gentile in Baal territory. The divine choice to send the prophet outside Israel and to bless the outsider is the precedent Jesus invokes for his own ministry\'s universal scope. Elijah\'s ministry to the Sidon widow is a type of Jesus\'s mission to the Gentiles: the rejected prophet brings life to those outside the covenant community who receive him in faith.</p>',
'27': '<p>"There were many in Israel with leprosy in the time of Elisha the prophet, yet not one of them was cleansed -- only Naaman the Syrian" (2 Kgs 5:1-14). Naaman was a general in the army of Aram -- Israel\'s enemy. He was cleansed; the many lepers in Israel were not. The divine freedom to heal whom he chooses, without regard for national identity or covenant membership, is the pattern Jesus establishes as the precedent for his own universalism. This prepares the reader for the Luke 17:16 healing of the Samaritan leper (the only one who returns to give thanks) and the Gentile mission of Acts.</p>',
'28': '<p>"All the people in the synagogue were furious when they heard this" (epl&#275;sth&#275;san thymon = were filled with rage) -- the prophetic word that exposes Israel\'s blindness produces rage rather than repentance. This is the pattern of the prophetic tradition: Jer 26:8-11 (Jeremiah nearly killed for his temple sermon); Amos 7:10-13 (expelled from Bethel); Acts 7:54 (Stephen\'s audience grinds their teeth). The fury at the Nazareth synagogue is the microcosm of the entire passion: the announcement of grace to the outsider, and the exposure of insider presumption, provokes murderous rejection.</p>',
'29': '<p>They "drove him out of the town and took him to the brow of the hill on which the town was built, in order to throw him down the cliff" -- the attempted stoning/cliff-throwing is a preview of the cross: the people of his hometown try to kill him by throwing him from a height. The "brow of the hill" (katakremnizo = throw down a cliff) is the method of execution used for blasphemers and rebels. Jesus will ultimately be "led outside the city" (Heb 13:12) to be crucified. The Nazareth crowd anticipates the Jerusalem crowd; the brow of the hill anticipates Golgotha. The rejection is complete and violent from the first.</p>',
'30': '<p>"But he walked right through the crowd and went on his way" -- the miraculous (or providential) escape through the crowd foreshadows the resurrection: Jesus passes through the barrier of death in the same way he passes through the barrier of the Nazareth crowd. John 10:17-18 establishes that Jesus\'s death is voluntary ("No one takes it from me, but I lay it down of my own accord"). His non-arrest at Nazareth demonstrates the same principle: he cannot be killed until the appointed time (22:53: "this is your hour"). The movement of the Son of Man through the crowd announces: the cross will happen at the Father\'s timing, not anyone else\'s.</p>',
'31': '<p>"Then he went down to Capernaum, a town in Galilee, and on the Sabbath he taught the people." Capernaum becomes Jesus\'s ministry headquarters (Matt 4:13: "making his home in Capernaum"). The movement from Nazareth (rejection) to Capernaum (ministry) fulfills Isa 9:1-2 (cited in Matt 4:15-16): "Galilee of the Gentiles... the people walking in darkness have seen a great light." Capernaum\'s archaeological identification (Tell Hum) is secure; the synagogue foundations there date to the first century. The Sabbath teaching demonstrates Jesus operating within the Jewish liturgical structure while bringing an authority that transcends it.</p>',
'32': '<p>"They were amazed at his teaching, because his words had authority (exousia)" -- exousia (authority, the right and power to command) is the Christological category that distinguishes Jesus from all previous teachers. The scribes taught by citation: "Rabbi X says... Rabbi Y says..." Jesus teaches as the one who gives the Torah its authoritative interpretation from within. Matt 5:21-48: "You have heard it was said... but I tell you." The exousia is divine authority exercised through human speech -- which is why the demons recognize it immediately (v.34) and why it shocks those trained to expect cited authority.</p>',
'33': '<p>The demon in the synagogue cries out at the presence of the Holy One of God. The juxtaposition is stark: in the place of worship, among those assembled to hear Torah, a demon has been present. The demon\'s presence in the synagogue is the state of Israel: the house of God occupied by the adversary. Jesus\'s exorcism in the synagogue is the first act of the stronger man entering the strong man\'s house (11:21-22) to plunder his goods. The demon\'s name reveals its taxonomy: it is "an impure spirit" -- the opposite of the Holy Spirit who anointed Jesus at his baptism.</p>',
'34': '<p>"I know who you are -- the Holy One of God!" -- the demon\'s declaration of Jesus\'s identity is demonically accurate (unlike the humans who misidentify or question him). "The Holy One of God" (ho hagios tou theou) is a messianic title rooted in Ps 16:10 (LXX: ton hosion sou = your Holy One, cited in Acts 2:27 and 13:35 as a resurrection prophecy) and in the prophet\'s title "man of God." The demons know what the disciples slowly come to understand: that Jesus is the divine Son. Their knowledge, however, is the knowledge of terror rather than faith (Jas 2:19: "even the demons believe... and shudder").</p>',
'35': '<p>"Be quiet! (Phimōthēti = be muzzled/silenced) Come out of him!" -- Jesus silences the demon\'s testimony and commands its departure. The silencing of demonic testimony (the messianic secret motif, though less prominent in Luke than in Mark) prevents the premature public declaration of Jesus\'s identity on the demon\'s terms. Jesus does not need or want satanic endorsements. The demon\'s public declaration of Jesus\'s identity at the synagogue would frame Jesus as a miracle-worker known to the spirit world -- not the kind of messianic reputation Jesus is building. He will be known by his teaching, his healings, his cross, and his resurrection -- not by demonic proclamation.</p>',
'36': '<p>"What words these are! With authority and power he gives orders to impure spirits and they come out!" -- the onlookers recognize a new category of authority: not merely the teaching authority of v.32 but command authority over the spirit world. Jesus is not exorcising by the standard methods of Jewish exorcism (Josephus Ant. 8.46-47 describes using a ring and root; the Tobit tradition uses incense and prayer). Jesus speaks one sentence and the demon obeys. This is the authority of the Creator speaking to the creation -- the same authority by which Jesus will command the sea (8:24: "He got up and rebuked the wind and the raging waters; the storm subsided").</p>',
'37': '<p>News about Jesus spreading "throughout the surrounding area" (eis panta topon = into every place) is the early movement of the Gospel. Acts 1:8 will give the program: Jerusalem, Judea, Samaria, the ends of the earth. The ministry of Luke 4-9 is the Galilean phase of that expansion. The spreading of Jesus\'s reputation is not merely sociological gossip but the beginning of the light that Isa 9:2 described: a light dawning on those who live in the shadow of death. Every time the Gospel spreads in Acts, Luke uses the same "throughout the region" language to mark geographic expansion of the Kingdom.</p>',
'38': '<p>"Jesus left the synagogue and went to the home of Simon." The movement from synagogue (public teaching) to house (private healing) models the two spaces of Jesus\'s ministry. Simon Peter\'s home in Capernaum has been archaeologically identified with reasonable confidence under the fifth-century octagonal church at Capernaum, which preserves a first-century dwelling. Peter\'s mother-in-law with a "high fever" (pyret&#333; megal&#333; = a great/high fever) -- Luke uses medical terminology throughout, consistent with the "beloved physician" tradition (Col 4:14). The fever is real and dangerous; the healing is real and total.</p>',
'39': '<p>"He bent over her and rebuked the fever, and it left her. She got up at once and began to wait on them" -- the rebuke of the fever (epetimēsen t&#333; pyret&#333; = rebuked the fever) uses the same verb as the demon-rebuke (v.35). Luke\'s framing treats illness and demonic oppression as related manifestations of the same fallen world condition. The immediate and total restoration ("she got up at once") distinguishes Jesus\'s healings from convalescence: not a gradual improvement but an instantaneous reversal of the condition. Her service (di&#275;konei autois = she was serving them) is the proper response to healing -- restored capacity immediately applied to service, the same pattern as Peter after Pentecost (Acts 2:41: three thousand added).</p>',
'40': '<p>"At sunset, the people brought to Jesus all who had various kinds of illness" -- sunset ended the Sabbath, allowing travel and seeking a healer. The crowds bringing their sick represent the fulfillment of Isa 53:4: "Surely he took up our pain and bore our suffering." Matt 8:16-17 makes this citation explicit in the parallel passage. The laying on of hands for healing (epitheis tas cheiras) was the standard Jewish gesture of blessing (Gen 48:14-18; Acts 6:6; 13:3) and one of the acts of the Messiah anticipated in the prophetic tradition. Jesus\'s hands on the sick enact the Servant\'s burden-bearing that Isaiah foresaw.</p>',
'41': '<p>"Demons came out of many people, shouting: You are the Son of God! But he rebuked them and would not allow them to speak, because they knew he was the Messiah." The demonic acknowledgment of Jesus as Son of God and Messiah comes from the spirit world\'s terrified recognition of the one who has come to destroy the devil\'s work (1 John 3:8: "The reason the Son of God appeared was to destroy the devil\'s work"). The silencing of demonic testimony is consistent with Jesus\'s practice: the Messiahship that the demons try to define on their terms must be disclosed on the Father\'s terms -- through teaching, suffering, death, and resurrection.</p>',
'42': '<p>Jesus withdrawing to a solitary place (eis erēmon topon = to a deserted/solitary place) for prayer is the recurring pattern of his ministry: before major decisions (6:12: all night before choosing the Twelve), after significant ministry (this verse), before the passion (22:41). The withdrawal to prayer establishes that Jesus\'s ministry flows from his communion with the Father, not from his own initiative. The people seeking him and trying to keep him from leaving mirrors the tension throughout the Gospel: the crowds want what Jesus gives (healing, teaching) without receiving what he is (the one who must go to Jerusalem to suffer and die).</p>',
'43': '<p>"I must proclaim the good news of the kingdom of God to the other towns also, because that is why I was sent" -- the dei (I must = divine necessity, the same dei of the passion predictions: 9:22; 17:25; 24:7, 26) applies here to the Galilean mission. Jesus is not driven by crowd demand or apostolic expectations but by the Father\'s mandate. "That is why I was sent" (epi touto apestalen = for this I was sent) echoes the Servant\'s commission in Isa 61:1-2 that Jesus read in the synagogue: the Spirit has sent him to proclaim. The entire itinerant ministry is obedience to a divine commission, not a charismatic impulse.</p>',
'44': '<p>"And he kept on preaching in the synagogues of Judea" -- Judea here probably means the whole Jewish territory (including Galilee), not just the southern region, which is how Luke uses it in 7:17. The systematic synagogue-by-synagogue preaching campaign is the practical fulfillment of the Isaiah 61 mandate: the good news of the Kingdom reaches every Jewish community in turn. This is the template that the early church follows in Acts: Paul and Barnabas go "first to the synagogue" in every city (Acts 13:14; 14:1; 17:1-2; 18:4). The synagogue mission of Acts is the continuation of the synagogue mission of Luke 4.</p>',
},
'5': {
'1': '<p>The Lake of Gennesaret (= the Sea of Galilee) is where the fishing economy of the region operated. The crowds pressing around Jesus to hear "the word of God" (ton logon tou theou = the word of God -- not just "his teaching") frames the scene in theological terms before the miracle: God\'s word is being proclaimed to Israel\'s working people beside Israel\'s waters. The scene deliberately echoes Ezek 47:9-10: Ezekiel\'s vision of the river flowing from the temple making the Dead Sea alive with fish, where "fishermen will stand along the shore." The miracle that follows activates this imagery.</p>',
'2': '<p>Two boats at the water\'s edge, fishermen washing their nets -- the detail of net-washing after a fruitless night (v.5) makes the subsequent miracle\'s impossibility vivid. Clean nets, put away, on boats pulled up to shore: everything signals the end of the working period. Simon\'s boat being available becomes the staging point for a public teaching that ends with a private miracle that transforms the fisher into a follower. The double structure (public word, private miracle, personal call) is the pattern of vocational calling throughout Luke-Acts.</p>',
'3': '<p>Jesus uses Simon\'s boat as a floating platform for teaching -- a detail that makes the subsequent miracle personal: Simon has served Jesus\'s teaching mission before being asked to serve him in the miraculous catch. The boat as pulpit resonates with the ship/boat symbolism in early Christianity (the church as the ark of salvation, with Christ as the helmsman -- a common patristic image). More immediately, it places Simon in a position of proximity and service before the theopanic encounter: he has been Jesus\'s host (4:38), now his boat-provider. The relationship precedes the call.</p>',
'4': '<p>"Put out into deep water (eis to bathos = into the depth) and let down the nets for a catch" -- the instruction to put out into the deep after a fruitless night reverses the normal pattern of Galilean fishing (shallow-water, night-time netting). The "deep" is also the theological register of the Psalms: "Out of the depths I cry to you, LORD" (Ps 130:1). Jesus commands an entry into the deep where human effort has produced nothing, which is exactly where the divine provision appears. The miracle tests faith in a word that contradicts experience and professional expertise.</p>',
'5': '<p>"Master (epistat&#275;), we\'ve worked hard all night and haven\'t caught anything. But because you say so, I will let down the nets" -- Simon\'s response is the model of obedient faith under contrary evidence. The "because you say so" (epi de t&#333; r&#275;mati sou = but at your word) is explicitly word-based obedience: Simon is acting not on his own fishing judgment but on Jesus\'s word alone. This is the same structure as the centurion\'s faith (7:7: "say the word and my servant will be healed") -- the recognition that Jesus\'s word alone is sufficient cause for action, regardless of contrary experience. This is the faith the resurrection will demand on a cosmic scale.</p>',
'6': '<p>"They caught such a large number of fish that their nets began to break" -- the miraculous catch of fish has been read typologically since the earliest commentators (Cyril of Alexandria, Ambrose): the fish = the souls drawn into the church\'s net through apostolic proclamation. John 21:11 records a second miraculous catch of 153 fish (after the resurrection), also connected explicitly to the apostolic mission. The breaking nets suggest a fullness that exceeds the capacity of the existing vessel -- the new-wine/new-wineskins saying (v.37-38) will articulate this same pattern: the new reality bursts old containers.</p>',
'7': '<p>The signal to partners and the two boats almost sinking from the weight is the communal dimension of apostolic work: Peter is not the only fisherman-disciple (James and John, sons of Zebedee, are partners). The "almost sinking" (h&#333;ste bythizesthai = so that they were going under) dramatizes the abundance: the miracle\'s fullness threatens the boats designed to contain it. This is an enacted parable of the Kingdom\'s abundance: the harvest is greater than any existing vessel can hold. The Lukan theme of the Kingdom\'s expansiveness recurs throughout: 5:39, 13:18-21, 14:22-23 (still room).</p>',
'8': '<p>"When Simon Peter saw this, he fell at Jesus\' knees and said: Go away from me, Lord; I am a sinful man" -- the theopanic response (falling, confession of unworthiness, request for distance) is the pattern of Isaiah\'s vision (Isa 6:5: "Woe to me! I am ruined! For I am a man of unclean lips") and Gideon\'s (Judg 6:22: "I have seen the angel of the LORD face to face! I will die!"). Peter recognizes that he is in the presence of the holy God and that such proximity is dangerous for a sinful human. "Lord" (kyrios) -- Peter\'s first use of the resurrection title for the earthly Jesus in Luke. The recognition precedes the calling: Peter knows who Jesus is before Jesus explains his mission.</p>',
'9': '<p>"For he and all his companions were astonished at the catch of fish they had taken" -- the astonishment (thambos = overwhelming wonder/amazement) is the human response to theophany throughout Luke (1:12; 4:36; 8:25; 9:43; 24:22). The astonishment is not merely psychological surprise at a remarkable event but the specific response of creatures encountering the holy. The miraculous catch of fish is a theophany -- the self-disclosure of the creator Lord in the midst of the ordinary. The fishing context emphasizes this: the Lord of creation is revealing his sovereignty in the domain of these men\'s ordinary work.</p>',
'10': '<p>"Don\'t be afraid; from now on you will fish for people" -- the "do not fear" (m&#275; phobou) is the standard divine reassurance after theophany (Gen 15:1; Josh 1:9; Isa 41:10; Luke 1:13, 30; 2:10; Acts 18:9; Rev 1:17). The commission transforms Simon\'s vocation: the skills of catching (z&#333;gr&#333;n = catching alive, taking alive, used of both fish and men in Greek) become the skills of apostolic proclamation. The implicit promise: the miraculous abundance of the fish catch -- thousands where Peter caught nothing -- will be repeated in the harvest of human souls. Acts 2:41 (3,000 on Pentecost) is the first fulfillment.</p>',
'11': '<p>"So they pulled their boats up on shore, left everything and followed him" -- the immediacy and completeness of the response (aphentes panta = having left everything) is the decisive mark of a call. The leave-everything motif runs through the disciple calls: Levi at 5:28, the rich ruler\'s failure at 18:22-23, and Peter\'s declaration at 18:28. "Following" (&#275;kolouth&#275;san = they followed, the imperfect of continuous action) inaugurates the discipleship relationship: they walk where he walks, learn what he teaches, see what he does. Everything from this point onward in the Gospel is experienced as followers of the one who called them.</p>',
'12': '<p>"A man covered with leprosy" fell on his face and begged: "Lord, if you are willing, you can make me clean." The double address to Jesus\'s will and power is the perfect prayer: "if you are willing" (ean th&#275;l&#275;s = if you desire, choose to) acknowledges sovereignty; "you can make me clean" (dynasai katharisai = you are able to cleanse me) acknowledges power. Levitical law required the leper to maintain distance (Lev 13:45-46); this man has prostrated himself at Jesus\'s feet. The act is both a violation of the purity code and an act of extraordinary faith: he comes near to the one whose holiness, he trusts, will cleanse rather than condemn him.</p>',
'13': '<p>"Jesus reached out his hand and touched the man. I am willing, be clean!" -- the touch (hapsamenos = having touched him) is the Christological act: Jesus touches the untouchable. Lev 5:3 specified that touching a person with an infectious skin disease made the toucher unclean. Jesus reverses the direction of contagion: his holiness flows into the leper rather than the leper\'s uncleanness flowing into Jesus. This is the logic of the Incarnation itself: the Holy One entering the unclean world does not become unclean but makes the unclean clean. The Incarnation is the supreme touch -- the Word becoming flesh to cleanse what flesh had defiled.</p>',
'14': '<p>"Go, show yourself to the priest and offer the sacrifices that Moses commanded for your cleansing, as a testimony to them" -- Jesus upholds the Mosaic purification procedure (Lev 14:2-32). The healed leper\'s priestly verification is the legitimate re-entry into the covenant community. The phrase "as a testimony to them" (eis martyrion autois = as a witness/testimony to them) is ambiguous: testimony to the priests of the healing? or testimony against them of what they are missing? The same phrase appears in 9:5 (shaking dust off feet "as a testimony against them"). Jesus honors the Torah while his action testifies that the era of the Law\'s promises is being fulfilled.</p>',
'15': '<p>"Yet the news about him spread all the more, so that crowds came to hear him and to be healed of their sicknesses" -- the growth pattern despite (or because of) Jesus\'s instruction for silence anticipates the unstoppable spread of the Gospel in Acts. Acts 5:14: "more and more men and women believed in the Lord and were added to their number." Acts 6:7: "the word of God spread... the number of disciples increased rapidly." Acts 12:24: "the word of God continued to spread and flourish." The Lukan pattern: the Word of God advances irresistibly, not by human strategy, but by the Spirit\'s sovereign work through human proclamation.</p>',
'16': '<p>"But Jesus often withdrew to lonely places and prayed" -- the pattern of Jesus\'s prayer retreat shapes the entire Lukan portrait: prayer before baptism (3:21), before choosing the Twelve (6:12), before the Transfiguration (9:28), at Gethsemane (22:41-44). The prayer of Jesus is not a devotional extra but the structural reality of his relationship with the Father that funds all ministry. The "lonely places" (tas er&#275;mous = the deserted places) echo the wilderness of the temptation: Jesus returns to the place of dependence and solitary communion whenever the crowd\'s demands multiply. His authority comes from this intimacy with the Father.</p>',
'17': '<p>The gathering of "Pharisees and teachers of the law" from "every village of Galilee and from Judea and Jerusalem" at a house where Jesus teaches creates the setting for the forgiveness controversy. The religious leadership of the nation assembles before the one who will forgive and heal in the same act. "The power of the Lord was present for him to heal" (dynamis kyriou ēn eis to iasthai auton = the power of the Lord was present for healing through him) -- the healing is the Lord\'s power working through the Son, not merely a natural ability. The presence of the Pharisees functions as the necessary witnesses for what follows: the declaration of the Son of Man\'s authority to forgive sins.</p>',
'18': '<p>Friends carrying a paralyzed man -- the four carry the helpless one to the only one who can help him. The paralytic cannot come to Jesus himself; he must be carried by others whose faith acts on his behalf. This is an enacted parable of intercession: the friends\' faith literally gets him to Jesus. "They tried to take him into the house to lay him before Jesus" -- the physical barriers are the barriers of a world that doesn\'t make it easy to get to Jesus. The friends will not be stopped. Their persistence anticipates the parable of the widow (18:1-8): faith does not give up at the first obstacle.</p>',
'19': '<p>Unable to get through the crowd, "they went up on the roof and lowered him on his mat through the tiles into the middle of the crowd, right in front of Jesus" -- the Palestinian house had a flat roof accessible by exterior stairs; the "tiles" suggest a Hellenized roof construction (Mark 4:4 has "digging through the roof"). The lowering of the paralytic into the middle of the crowd is a feat of determination and improvisation. The dramatic entrance through the roof means the paralytic literally descends to Jesus -- a Christological image for the humble approach to the Son of Man who came down from heaven (John 6:38: "I have come down from heaven").</p>',
'20': '<p>"When Jesus saw their faith, he said: Friend, your sins are forgiven" -- the first response is not healing but forgiveness. Jesus addresses the paralytic as "friend" (anthr&#333;pe = man, literally -- a somewhat familiar/warm address). The forgiveness (apheōntai = have been forgiven, perfect passive: the forgiving has been done and stands) precedes the healing. This sequence is the theological argument: the deepest human need is not physical restoration but forgiveness of sins. The healing will follow as the sign that forgiveness has actually occurred. Jesus treats the moral/spiritual condition as primary and the physical condition as secondary -- the opposite of what the crowd and the religious authorities expect.</p>',
'21': '<p>"Who is this fellow who speaks blasphemy? Who can forgive sins but God alone?" -- the Pharisees\' theological objection is technically correct: only God can forgive sins (Isa 43:25: "I, even I, am he who blots out your transgressions"; Mark 2:7 parallel). Their error is not in the theology but in the Christological conclusion they fail to draw. If Jesus forgives sins and the healing confirms it, then their premise leads to a conclusion they will not accept: this man is God. The objection that "only God can forgive" is an implicit Christological argument that cuts both ways -- if Jesus forgives sins and is authenticated, then he is who he says he is.</p>',
'22': '<p>"Jesus knew what they were thinking and asked: Why are you thinking these things in your hearts?" -- the knowledge of thoughts (eidōs tas enthumēseis = knowing the inner reasonings/thoughts) is a divine attribute in the OT (1 Chr 28:9: "the LORD searches every heart and understands every desire and every thought"; Ps 139:2). The silent objection in the Pharisees\' hearts is known to Jesus as clearly as spoken words. This is a revelation of God: the one who knows hearts is present. The subsequent question turns the Pharisees\' logic against them: they are asked to decide which statement is easier to make, which will expose the deeper question of authority.</p>',
'23': '<p>"Which is easier: to say, your sins are forgiven, or to say, get up and walk?" -- the question is epistemologically sharp. To say "your sins are forgiven" is empirically unverifiable: no one can observe whether forgiveness has actually occurred. To say "get up and walk" is immediately falsifiable: if the man doesn\'t walk, the word has failed. Jesus uses the verifiable act (healing) as the sign that confirms the unverifiable act (forgiveness). The logic: if I can command the physical body and have it obey, this demonstrates the authority behind the spiritual declaration. The miracle is not the main act but the evidence for the main act.</p>',
'24': '<p>"But I want you to know that the Son of Man has authority on earth to forgive sins" -- the Son of Man\'s authority to forgive sins is a Christological claim of the highest order. Daniel 7:13-14 gives "the Son of Man" universal dominion; Jesus here claims that this universal dominion includes authority that belongs exclusively to God -- the forgiveness of sins. The combination of the Daniel title with the divine prerogative of forgiveness is the central offense of the passion: 22:69-70 (Son of Man + Son of God = blasphemy charge). Jesus enacts here what the Sanhedrin will condemn him for later -- and the healing is the ongoing sign that his claim is true.</p>',
'25': '<p>"Immediately he stood up in front of them, took what he had been lying on and went home praising God" -- the immediacy and completeness of the healing is the authentication Jesus claimed. The man who was carried in on a mat leaves carrying it: the reversal is total. "Praising God" (dox&#257;z&#333;n ton theon = glorifying God) is the proper response to the forgiveness and healing. It directs the praise to the Father rather than to Jesus, consistent with Jesus\'s own practice (10:21: "I praise you, Father"). The man\'s healing and praise together demonstrate what the forgiveness of sins produces in those who receive it: restored mobility and worship.</p>',
'26': '<p>"Everyone was amazed and gave praise to God. They were filled with awe and said: We have seen remarkable things today" (eidamen paradoxa s&#275;meron = we have seen extraordinary/paradoxical things today) -- paradoxa (paradox, extraordinary things, things beyond expectation) is the word for events that contradict normal expectations. The healing of the paralytic is a paradox in both the physical and theological sense: a man who couldn\'t move walked; a man who could only be forgiven by God was forgiven by a Galilean teacher. The "today" (s&#275;meron) echoes v.21 ("today this scripture is fulfilled") -- the eschatological today of Jesus\'s ministry is when extraordinary things happen.</p>',
'27': '<p>"After this, Jesus went out and saw a tax collector by the name of Levi sitting at his tax booth. Follow me, Jesus said to him" -- Levi\'s call parallels Simon\'s (v.1-11): both are called from their normal occupation by a direct command with no prior preparation. The tax collector\'s booth (tel&#333;nion = the customs/tax-collection post) was a position of social infamy (tax collectors were regarded as traitors and extortioners). The call of Levi demonstrates the same principle as the leper\'s cleansing: Jesus extends his touch to the untouchable. The community Jesus is forming includes those whom polite Jewish society excluded -- anticipating the church that Acts describes.</p>',
'28': '<p>"And Levi got up, left everything and followed him" -- "left everything" (kat&#275;lipen panta = left behind all things) parallels the fishermen\'s call (v.11: "left everything"). The completeness of the response is emphasized in both cases. For Levi the cost is economic as well as social: his tax booth represents ongoing income that cannot be recovered. This is more costly than the fishermen\'s nets, which can be returned to. The fact that Levi hosts a great banquet (v.29) suggests he has the resources to make this sacrifice. Generosity in the face of loss is the response of those who understand what they have received.</p>',
'29': '<p>Levi "held a great banquet for Jesus at his house, and a large crowd of tax collectors and others were eating with them" -- the banquet is the proper response to grace: celebration, hospitality, and inviting others to share. The guest list -- "tax collectors and others" (hamart&#333;loi = sinners, as the Pharisees call them in v.30) -- is the first visible sign of the new community Jesus is forming. The table fellowship with sinners is the enacted parable of the Kingdom: the great banquet of 14:15-24 where the originally invited refuse and the poor/lame/blind/sinners are brought in. The Messiah\'s table is not for the self-righteous but for those who know their need.</p>',
'30': '<p>"But the Pharisees and the teachers of the law who belonged to their sect complained to his disciples: Why do you eat and drink with tax collectors and sinners?" -- eating together (commensality) in the first-century Mediterranean world was an act of social identification: you eat with those who are your equals or your clients. To eat with "sinners" was to identify with them and implicitly to endorse their behavior. The Pharisees\' complaint is socially intelligible: the table fellowship is a public statement about who belongs to the covenant community. Jesus\'s answer redefines the covenant community\'s boundaries.</p>',
'31': '<p>"It is not the healthy who need a doctor, but the sick" -- the physician metaphor for Jesus appears in 4:23 as a challenge (physician, heal yourself) and here as a self-description. Jesus identifies himself as the doctor who goes to the sick. In Jewish tradition, God is the physician (Exod 15:26: "I am the LORD who heals you"). Jesus\'s self-description as physician places him in the role that God claimed for himself in the Exodus. The logic is gracious: the doctor\'s presence is required by those who need him, not by those who don\'t. Jesus is present among sinners because sinners are where the physician is needed.</p>',
'32': '<p>"I have not come to call the righteous, but sinners to repentance" -- the explicit statement of mission: Jesus came (elthon = I came, the aorist of a completed coming from somewhere) to call sinners. The combination of "call" (kalesai = to summon, invite) and "repentance" (metanoian = a change of mind/direction) frames the Gospel as an invitation. The "righteous" are those who, like the Pharisees, do not recognize their need. The calling of sinners fulfills Isa 55:7: "Let the wicked forsake their ways and the unrighteous their thoughts. Let them turn to the LORD, and he will have mercy on them." Jesus is the voice crying in the wilderness, calling the lost to return.</p>',
'33': '<p>"John\'s disciples often fast and pray, and so do the disciples of the Pharisees, but yours go on eating and drinking" -- the fasting question is a question about eschatology: fasting is an act of mourning, waiting, and longing for the Kingdom\'s arrival. John\'s disciples and the Pharisees fast because the Kingdom has not yet arrived. Jesus\'s disciples feast because the bridegroom is present (v.34). The controversy about fasting is a controversy about whether the messianic age has begun. Jesus\'s answer ("the bridegroom is with them") is the implicit claim: the age of the Kingdom has begun. The feast is appropriate; fasting would be a denial of the eschatological reality.</p>',
'34': '<p>"Can you make the friends of the bridegroom fast while he is with them?" -- the bridegroom imagery is drawn from the OT\'s description of God as Israel\'s husband (Isa 54:5: "your Maker is your husband"; Hos 2:16-20; Jer 31:32). John the Baptist had identified himself as the friend of the bridegroom who rejoices at the bridegroom\'s voice (John 3:29). Jesus is the bridegroom -- a divine title -- who is now present with his people. The feasting that his presence requires is the eschatological feast of the Kingdom. Paul will use the same imagery (2 Cor 11:2: "I promised you to one husband, to Christ") and Revelation will culminate it (Rev 19:7: "the wedding of the Lamb").</p>',
'35': '<p>"But the time will come when the bridegroom will be taken from them; in those days they will fast" -- "taken away" (apath&#275; = is taken away from them, removed) is the language of sudden violent removal (cf. Isa 53:8 LXX: "his life was taken from the earth"). Jesus predicts his violent removal from the disciples\' presence -- the cross -- as the event that will reactivate fasting. The post-ascension church fasts (Acts 13:2-3; 14:23) because the bridegroom has been taken, though they fast in hope rather than despair: the wedding feast awaits (Rev 19:9). The verse frames the passion as the interval between the first and second coming.</p>',
'36': '<p>"No one tears a piece out of a new garment to patch an old one" -- the new/old garment parable is the first of three analogies for the relationship between Jesus\'s ministry and the existing structure of Judaism. The new cloth tears when used to patch the old: both are destroyed -- the new coat is ruined, the old coat is not properly fixed. Jesus\'s teaching is not a patch for a worn-out religion. The covenant he brings is not a reform of the existing covenant but a new covenant -- which is why Jer 31:31 uses the word "new" (h&#257;d&#257;sh&#257;h = new, unprecedented, of a different kind). The new patch/old garment = the incompatibility of the new covenant with the old legal-religious structure.</p>',
'37': '<p>"And no one pours new wine into old wineskins. Otherwise, the new wine will burst the skins; the wine will run out and the wineskins will be ruined" -- old dried wineskins had lost the elasticity to expand with fermenting new wine; they would burst. New wineskins were still flexible. The fermentation process of new wine is the Spirit\'s active, expansive work (Acts 2:13: the crowd at Pentecost says the disciples are "filled with new wine"). The new covenant -- the Spirit poured out, forgiveness given freely, Jew and Gentile one community -- cannot be contained within the rigid legal structures of the old covenant. The wineskin imagery announces the structural incompatibility, not the abolition of the old but its completion and transcendence.</p>',
'38': '<p>"No, new wine must be poured into new wineskins" -- the positive statement completes the analogy. The new wine requires new vessels: the new covenant requires new structures (the church as the new covenant community), new practices (baptism and the Lord\'s Supper replacing circumcision and Passover as the covenant sign and covenant meal), and new understanding (the Spirit illuminating the Scriptures to reveal Christ throughout). Paul makes the same argument in 2 Cor 3:6-14 and Gal 4:21-31: the old and new covenants are not compatible in the sense that the old cannot contain what the new has inaugurated.</p>',
'39': '<p>"And no one after drinking old wine wants the new, for they say: The old is better" -- this saying is unique to Luke and is often overlooked. It is not a condemnation of those who prefer the old but a realistic observation about human inertia: those accustomed to the old covenant\'s ways (the Pharisees, the disciples of John) will not immediately prefer the new. The old is familiar and comfortable; the new requires adjustment. The saying is not cynical but realistic -- it explains why the Pharisees resist Jesus\'s new wine rather than dismissing them as simply wicked. The resistance to Jesus is partly the resistance of all humans to genuine newness, which is always costly to receive.</p>',
}
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', 'luke')
    merge_comm(existing, NEW)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', 'luke', existing)
    import json as _j, pathlib as _pl
    inter = _j.loads((_pl.Path(__file__).parent.parent / 'data/interlinear/luke.json').read_text())
    for ch in [4, 5]:
        ck = str(ch)
        have = set(existing.get(ck, {}).keys())
        need = set(inter.get(ck, {}).keys())
        missing = sorted(int(v) for v in (need - have))
        print(f'  ch{ch}: {len(have)}/{len(need)} -- missing: {missing}')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
